Moscow News noted that in 1975, in a tract titled Knowledge and the World, Sakharov set forth his views on Soviet affairs. Sakharov, a brilliant physicist, was allowed to return to Moscow in December 1986 from his forced residence in the closed city of Gorky, where he was banished without trial in January 1980. This week's issue of the newspaper Moscow News said that Sakharov long ago understood the need for change in the Soviet Union.  Sakharov a traitor, but a Moscow weekly has now provided a sympathetic portrait of the human rights activist and his wife. 